# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: campanino
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:campanino/adams-pearmain] '**Adams Pearmain**', also called '**Adam's Parmane**', is a cultivar of apple.
[src:campanino/adams-pearmain] It was introduced to the Horticultural Society of London in 1826 by Robert Adams, under the name '**Norfolk Pippin**'.
[src:campanino/adams-pearmain] The fruit is large, varying from two and a half inches to three inches high, and about the same in breadth at the widest part.
[src:campanino/adams-pearmain] It is pearmain-shaped, very even, and regularly formed.
[src:campanino/adams-pearmain] The skin is pale yellow tinged with green, and covered with delicate russet on the shaded side; but deep yellow tinged with red, and delicately streaked with livelier red on the side facing the sun.
[src:campanino/adams-pearmain] The flesh is reddish, crisp, juicy, rich, and sugary, with an agreeable and pleasantly perfumed flavor.
[src:campanino/adams-pearmain] This Cultivar is a sibling of Reinette de Hollande, a hybrid between Reinette Franche’ and ‘Reinette des Carmes.
[src:campanino/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has large apples, weighing from 250 to 300 grams.
[src:campanino/aia-ilu] It is juicy, bittersweet, and has a weak aroma.
[src:campanino/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu is grown in nurseries, but is not widely propagated.
[src:campanino/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has low scab resistance and is resistant to powdery mildew.
[src:campanino/airlie-red-flesh] Oregon apple with bright pink flesh and speckled green skin.
[src:campanino/airlie-red-flesh] The **Airlie Red Flesh**, (also known as the **Hidden Rose** or the **Mountain Rose**), is a cultivar of domesticated apple.
[src:campanino/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh tree will grow to a height of 4 meters (13 ft) to 5 meters (16 ft), and starts to fruit after about 4 years of growing.
[src:campanino/airlie-red-flesh] Airlie Red Flesh fruits are medium-sized, often small.
[src:campanino/airlie-red-flesh] The flavour of an Airlie Red Flesh apple has a balance of sweetness and tartness.
[src:campanino/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple has dark red flesh and a crisp texture.
[src:campanino/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple tends to ripen in late September.
[src:campanino/akane-apple] '**Akane'**, also known as '**Tokyo Rose'**, '**Tohoku No.3'** and '**Prime Red'**, is a Japanese cultivar of domesticated apple, that according to Orange Pippin is one of the best early season apples.
[src:campanino/akane-apple] 'Akane' was developed by the Morika Experimental Station of Japan sometime between 1900 and 1949, by crossing a Jonathan apple with a Worcester Pearmain, and was introduced to the United States in 1937, where it is very popular.
[src:campanino/akane-apple] 'Akane' is of moderately good disease resistance, best at warm climates but tolerates cold also.
[src:campanino/akane-apple] It flowers mid-late season, and should be harvested early-mid season.
[src:campanino/akane-apple] It is self-sterile and needs to be cross pollinated.
[src:campanino/akane-apple] It produces heavy crop of variable sized fruits, usually more to the smaller side, but good sized apples can be obtained by thinning.
[src:campanino/akane-apple] 'Akane' carries the fruit shape of the English 'Worcester Pearmain', and the unusually good balanced flavor of the 'Jonathan'.
[src:campanino/akane-apple] Shape ranges from flattened to heart-shaped.
[src:campanino/akane-apple] Fruits have a very good flavor, a blend of sweet and sharp, preferable for eating, keeps shape in cooking.
[src:campanino/akane-apple] Flesh color is white, with a yellow tinge.
[src:campanino/akane-apple] The apple is crisp, but not too dense; it is easy to eat.
[src:campanino/akane-apple] The fruit keeps fresh for about one week.
[src:campanino/alkmene-apple] '**Alkmene'** is a German cultivar of domesticated apple, also called '**Early Windsor'**.
[src:campanino/alkmene-apple] Two natural mutations (sports) of this cultivar that have red-skinned fruit have been selected: one called '**Red Alkmene'** was trademarked under the name of **Red Windsor**; the other is '**Ceeval'**.
[src:campanino/alkmene-apple] It was developed between 1900 and 1949, by the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute in Müncheberg, Germany, by crossing the two cultivars 'Cox's Orange Pippin' and 'Geheimrat Dr.
[src:campanino/alkmene-apple] Oldenburg' (frequently confused with the similar-sounding 'Duchess of Oldenburg').
[src:campanino/alkmene-apple] The result is an early harvest apple (early mid season), which is very attractive, with a honeyed flavor similar to Cox's but slightly sharper.
[src:campanino/alkmene-apple] 'Alkmene' flowers early mid season, with self-fertile blossoms, hence no cross pollination is needed.
[src:campanino/alkmene-apple] Fruit size is medium and variable, flesh color is yellowish or extremely yellow for an apple, skin has greenish-yellow background with orange-reddish flush and strong red strips.
[src:campanino/alkmene-apple] The 'Red Windsor' cultivar has a larger portion of red.
[src:campanino/alkmene-apple] It is resistant to apple scab and susceptible to blossom frost.
[src:campanino/alkmene-apple] 'Alkmene' was awarded the Award of Garden Merit by the Royal Horticultural Society in 1998.
[src:campanino/allington-pippin] '**Allington Pippin'** is an English cultivar of domesticated apple, with a strong flavour that includes hints of pineapple.
[src:campanino/allington-pippin] The Allington Pippin was developed prior to year 1884 by Thomas Laxton in Lincolnshire, England through a cross breeding of Cox's Orange Pippin and the King of the Pippins.
[src:campanino/allington-pippin] This name was not given until 1894, when George Bunyard named it after the village of Allington near Maidstone in Kent, where one of the Bunyard's nurseries was situated.
[src:campanino/allington-pippin] This apple is conical shaped and its outer skin is combined from flashy colours of red and orange, flushed and striped, with some russeting.
[src:campanino/allington-pippin] Its special mellowing to sharp fruit candy or pineapple flavour is appreciated in multipurpose use: cooking, fresh eating and flavourful apple cider.
[src:campanino/allington-pippin] Allington is rather a strong fruit, it has a good storage record of three months or more, and keeps shape in cooking.
[src:campanino/allington-pippin] 'Allington Pippin' has a biennial bearing tendency, flowers are partially self-sterile, mid season; harvest period is late.
[src:campanino/allington-pippin] The tree is average on general tendency to diseases, but blossom is susceptible to frost.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] Its colour, juice content, sweetness, and overall flavour have made the Ambrosia one of the most purchased apples in numerous countries.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] The Ambrosia apple tree has an upright growth pattern, varying on soil quality, rootstock, environment, and management.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] The tree develops lateral branches, requiring pruning to maintain vigour and fruit size.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] In the first two years of growth, significant tree training is needed to assure well-angled fruiting branches and productivity.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] Ambrosia apple trees are suitable for dense planting, have high yields, and require little pruning during the winter.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] Pollinating partners of the Ambrosia include the Cortland, Fuji, and Granny Smith.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] The fruit is medium to large, 6.8–7.5 cm (2.7–3.0 in) in diameter, weighing about 215 grams (0.474 lb), and has mostly red, glossy colouration, with yellow patches.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] It has cream-coloured, firm, and juicy texture, with a mild and sweet flavour reminiscent of pear and low acidity, with the flesh resisting oxidation, making it suitable for salads and fresh fruit displays.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] These apples flower in the mid-to-late blossom period, and are harvested in mid-to-late season (mid-September in its native Similkameen Valley of British Columbia; September–October in Ontario, mid-October in Quebec).
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] Ambrosia apples produce a low amount of ethylene, not displaying the usual climacteric rise at harvest.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] Accordingly, internal ethylene concentrations do not indicate accurate fruit maturity, whereas skin colour and starch staining charts are commonly used for optimal harvest and standardization of fruit quality.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] Orchard irrigation conditions appear to be a factor causing soft scald and reduced quality of Ambrosia apples during storage.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] Derived from a chance seedling, the Ambrosia is suspected to be a cross of the Starking Delicious and the Golden Delicious because those apples existed in the orchard where the Ambrosia was discovered growing.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] Ambrosia is a "club" variety of apple, in which a cultivar is patented by an organization that sets quality standards and provides marketing, while production is limited to club members.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] Centralized control allowed limitation of color variation to pink/red, as the variety would colour differently in warmer climates.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] The patent expired in Canada in 2015, in the United States in 2017, and in Chile in 2021.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] It remains active in many other countries until as late as 2034.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] While under patent in Canada, the Mennell family obtained plant breeders rights, and all growers were allowed, paying a royalty of CA$2–3.75 per tree planting.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] While under patent in the US, growers paid the lesser of US$1 per tree planting or US$1,000 per acre, and a US$1,000 franchise fee.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] The Ambrosia Gold is marketed as the premium version of this variety.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] Ambrosia is most commonly cultivated in British Columbia, where it was the third most-produced apple in 2016.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] By the mid 2020s, British Columbia continues to take the lead in production, followed by Ontario and Nova Scotia.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] Alongside the Honeycrisp and Gala, the Ambrosia has risen in prominence among Canadian farmers and consumers at the expense of the Red Delicious.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] In the United States, the majority of Ambrosia apples are harvested in Washington State and New York.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] This variety is also grown in Chile, New Zealand, the Netherlands, and Italy, among other countries.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] In the early 21st century, it is one of the most popular apple varieties in Canada and the United States, especially in the South and Midwest.
[src:campanino/ambrosia-apple] It has also found success in the Asian market, notably Vietnam.
[src:campanino/campanino] Campanino apples are included in the list of Italian traditional foodstuffs (*Prodotti agroalimentari tradizionali* – PAT) from the Emilia-Romagna region, and in the Emilia-Romagna Regional Voluntary Database of Agricultural Genetic Resources (code RER V019).
[src:campanino/campanino] The *cultivar* is also widespread in the Veneto region, where it is called *campanìn* (code GM27) or *Modena apple* (code GM47).
[src:campanino/campanino] The ancient origins of this variety are not known.
[src:campanino/campanino] In 1815, Italian pomologist Georges Gallesio described a seedling found in the province of Modena as "Modena apple".
[src:campanino/campanino] In 1877 historian Don Felice Ceretti from Mirandola, published an article in a local periodical in which he spoke about "apples called *campanini* which are widely stocked in autumn and transported to Venice and other cities".
[src:campanino/campanino] After the Second World War, cultivation of Campanino apples decreased in favour of other varieties that are more productive, easier to grow, and more appreciated by consumers.
[src:campanino/campanino] Historian Vilmo Cappi (1918–2013) wrote that the Campanino apple was disappearing because it was being replaced by more commercial varieties and types of apples.
[src:campanino/campanino] There are still those, however, who prefer the fruit since it can last all winter long with its fragrance kept intact while its clean and white pulp looks like marble.
[src:campanino/campanino] The fruits of the Campanino apple tree are small, usually symmetrical, and usually spheroidal (about 64 millimetres (2.5 in) in diameter by 58 millimetres (2.3 in) in height), with a weight of about 85–95 grams (3.0–3.4 oz).
[src:campanino/campanino] The skin is thick and not very waxy, of a yellow-green colour which becomes red-green when the fruit is exposed to sunlight.
[src:campanino/campanino] The flesh is greenish-white, very firm, and sugary.
[src:campanino/campanino] It is also aromatic and slightly acidic.
[src:campanino/campanino] A scientific study carried out by the University of Bologna on characteristics of five ancient varieties of apple highlighted Campanino's qualities.
[src:campanino/campanino] It contains high amounts of antioxidants (up to four times more than *Golden Delicious* apples), high content of pectin and polyphenols, as well as ascorbic acid (vitamin C).
[src:campanino/campanino] The flowering season occurs in April–May, and the apple can be harvested for about a month from the beginning of October.
[src:campanino/campanino] Matured *Campaninas* have red skin colouration especially after they have been exposed to the sun for 5–7 days: for this reason Campanina apple is also called as the "Annurca apple of Northern Italy".
[src:campanino/campanino] Unlike other varieties, Campanino apples can be easily preserved for six months without any use of refrigeration.
[src:campanino/campanino] This characteristic has allowed the survival of Campanino variety until today.
[src:campanino/campanino] The Campanino apple growing area is located in the Northeast Italy, in the provinces of Ferrara, Mantua, Modena, Reggio Emilia and Rovigo.
[src:campanino/campanino] The variety is also widespread in the province of Venice, where it is known as "*Modenese* apple".
[src:campanino/campanino] Campanino is often used as a cooking apple since its flesh remains intact and compact even after cooking.
[src:campanino/campanino] It is also excellent when eaten fresh as it retains all its nutrients even months after being harvested.
[src:campanino/campanino] The Campanino apple can be eaten raw, but because of its thick skin, people prefer it for cooking, preferably in a casserole with a little water, and a simple dusting of sugar, which is then caramelized in the oven.
[src:campanino/campanino] The apple's pulp is used to make jam, *mostarda* (including *Mostarda di Mantova*), and *savór*, or ingredients for apple pie or pancakes.
[src:campanino/campanino] Traditional mostarda, a sweet-and-hot condiment made from Campanina apples or quinces, sugar and mustard, has been served with boiled meats as far back as the Middle Ages.
